{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525194"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:13:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:13:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14065"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14065"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.7,0.02,0.22,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55797"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6724"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14065"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41342"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2887"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16015"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16213"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44884"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55797"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of severe vertigo, nausea, and vomiting that began two hours ago. She also reports a sharp pain in the back of her neck that started yesterday after a vigorous yoga session. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 145/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals nystagmus, and left-sided ataxia. There is also decreased pain and temperature sensation on the left side of her face, along with decreased pain and temperature sensation on the right side of her trunk. Cranial nerve examination is otherwise normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo","Vertebral artery dissection","Meniere\u0027s disease","Cerebellar stroke","Vestibular neuritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Evertebral artery dissection\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient presents with acute onset vertigo accompanied by neck pain, which is a classic presentation of vertebral artery dissection. The recent history of vigorous yoga is a potential risk factor, as neck manipulation or sudden movements can lead to arterial dissection. The neurological examination findings of nystagmus, ataxia, and crossed sensory deficits (ipsilateral ataxia, ipsilateral pain/temperature loss on the face, and and contralateral pain/temperature loss on the trunk) are consistent with lateral medullary syndrome, which can result from vertebral artery dissection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV)\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with brief episodes of vertigo triggered by changes in head position. It does not cause persistent vertigo or neurological deficits as seen in this patient. Additionally, BPPV is not associated with neck pain or a recent history of neck manipulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVestibular neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause acute vertigo with nausea and vomiting, but it does not typically cause neck pain or neurological deficits beyond the vestibular system. The presence of ataxia and sensory changes makes vestibular neuritis less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeniere\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by recurrent episodes of vertigo, fluctuating hearing loss, tinnitus, and aural fullness. The acute onset and associated neurological deficits in this patient are not typical of Meniere\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebellar stroke\u003C/strong\u003E can present with acute vertigo and ataxia, and remains an important differential diagnosis. However, the presence of neck pain and the specific pattern of neurological deficits (lateral medullary syndrome) are more suggestive of vertebral artery dissection. It\u0027s worth noting that vertebral artery dissection can lead to cerebellar stroke if not promptly diagnosed and treated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn cases of suspected vertebral artery dissection, urgent neuroimaging (preferably MRI/MRA or CTA) is crucial to confirm the diagnosis and guide management. Treatment typically involves anticoagulation or antiplatelet therapy to prevent thromboembolic complications, and close monitoring for neurological deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vertebral artery dissection can present with acute onset vertigo, neck pain, and neurological deficits.","The presence of risk factors and associated symptoms helps differentiate vertebral artery dissection from more common causes of vertigo.","Urgent neuroimaging is crucial in suspected vertebral artery dissection to confirm the diagnosis and guide management."],"references":["Williams DR, Bertram KL. Neck pain: What if it is not musculoskeletal. Australian Journal of General Practice 2018. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/getattachment/c2ba861d-05a4-4a40-9a6f-3f1748d7d716/Neck-pain.aspx","Physiopedia. Wallenberg Syndrome. n.d. Physio-pedia. Available from: https://www.physio-pedia.com/Wallenberg_Syndrome#cite_note-Nicholson-3","Day GS, Swartz RH, Chenkin J, Shamji AI, Frost DW. Lateral medullary syndrome: a diagnostic approach illustrated through case presentation and literature review. CJEM. 2014 Mar;16(2):164-70. doi: 10.2310/8000.2013.131059. PMID: 24626124."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41342"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14065"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41342"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T22:56:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T09:29:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6724"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55797"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}}